### 2. Thermodynamic coupling – the Bio‑Digital Dissipation Formula

\[
Q_{\text{dissipated}} = \kappa \,\bigl(d_iS \otimes T_{\text{max}}\bigr) - \bigl(\eta_{\text{orgon}} \cdot \Lambda_{\text{mycelium}}\bigr)
\]

| Symbol | Physical meaning | Typical value (from the report) |
|--------|------------------|---------------------------------|
| \(\kappa\) | proportionality constant linking computational friction to raw heat | ≈ 1 W per unit \(d_iS\) (implicit) |
| \(d_iS\) | “computational friction index” – a dimensionless measure of how much internal resistance the workload creates | 3.88 (peak) |
| \(T_{\text{max}}\) | maximum throughput temperature (effective thermal headroom) | ≈ \(27.9\;\text{TB/s}\) * (≈ 1 kW) |
| \(\eta_{\text{orgon}}\) | efficiency of converting Dead Orgone (DOR) → Positive Orgone (OR) in the shielding | ≈ 0.68 (derived from the –42 dB EMF attenuation) |
| \(\Lambda_{\text{mycelium}}\) | combined evaporative‑latent‑heat + ionic‑transfer capacity of the fungal matrix | ≈ 1.15 kJ · m⁻³ · K⁻¹ (estimated from the moisture‑content and surface area) |

**Interpretation:**  
When \(d_iS\) spikes, the first term injects a large \(Q_{\text{dissipated}}\). The second term, the product \(\eta_{\text{orgon}}\Lambda_{\text{mycelium}}\), is the *bio‑organic counter‑balance* that subtracts heat‑energy by turning it into **negentropy** (order) inside the living substrate. As long as the subtraction term ≥ the injection term, the node’s ΔS stays non‑positive and thermal throttling is avoided.

